1Ô∏è‚É£ GROUP BY Clause

Purpose:
GROUP BY is used to group rows that have the same values into summary rows, often used with aggregate functions like
COUNT(), SUM(), AVG(), MIN(), and MAX().

üíª Example 1: Average Salary by Department
SELECT department, AVG(salary) AS average_salary
FROM employees
GROUP BY department;


üß© Output:

| department | average_salary |
| ---------- | -------------- |
| HR         | 45000          |
| IT         | 72000          |
| Sales      | 52000          |

üí° Explanation:

Groups employees by department

Calculates the average salary for each group

üîπ 2Ô∏è‚É£ HAVING Clause

Purpose:
HAVING filters the groups created by GROUP BY, just like WHERE filters individual rows.

üíª Example 2: Show departments where average salary > 50,000
SELECT department, AVG(salary) AS average_salary
FROM employees
GROUP BY department
HAVING AVG(salary) > 50000;


üß© Output:

| department | average_salary |
| ---------- | -------------- |
| IT         | 72000          |
| Sales      | 52000          |

‚öñÔ∏è Difference Between WHERE and HAVING:

Clause	Used For	Works On
WHERE	Filters rows before grouping	Individual records
HAVING	Filters after grouping	
